******
[3] Nebraska
Date: Fri 26 Jun 2020
Source: Nebraska TV [edited]
https://nebraska.tv/news/local/nda-confirms-vesicular-stomatitis-case-in-a-horse-in-buffalo-county


The Nebraska Department of Agriculture (NDA) has confirmed a case of vesicular stomatitis (VS) in a horse in Buffalo County, and the horse has been quarantined. One additional horse on the premises is also exhibiting symptoms, therefore all animals on the infected premises will be quarantined for at least 14 days.

VS is a viral disease that primarily affects horses and cattle, but can also affect sheep, goats, and swine, the press release added.

"Vesicular Stomatitis is primarily transmitted through the bite of infected black flies, sand flies, and midges," said State Veterinarian Dr. Dennis Hughes. "There are things livestock owners can do to reduce flies and other insects where animals are housed, but until freezing temperatures move in and kill the insects that spread the virus, VS will continue to be a threat in Nebraska."

Hughes added, "Since VS can also spread by contact between animals and by shared equipment, like tools or tack, we want livestock owners to be aware and practice good biosecurity measures with their animals, particularly with animals that may comingle with others."

Nebraska has import restrictions for livestock coming into the state from states that have confirmed VS cases to help prevent VS.

If you are considering moving an animal into Nebraska from an affected state, please call 402-471-2351.

"The virus itself usually runs its course in 5-7 days, and it can take up to an additional 7 days for an infected animal to recover from the symptoms," said Hughes.

To avoid human exposure, people should use personal protective measures when handling affected animals.

For more information on VS, click here: https://nebraska.tv/news/local/nda-confirms-vesicular-stomatitis-case-in-a-horse-in-buffalo-county.

[Byline: KHGI]

